http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers which feature general news stories and which
      focus on specific topics such as livestock, animal culture, produce, farm life,
      etc.

Use for newspapers published for towns where one main company
      employs most of the community.

Use for newspapers produced for local or national Evangelical or
      missionary audiences. May be published by a church or non-denominational
      group

Use for newspapers advocating the legal prevention of the
      manVFacture and sale of alcoholic beverages.

Use for newspapers which report on competitive exhibitions of farm
      products, livestock, baked goods, etc. with prizes for excellence, often combined with
      carnival-like entertainment, and held annually by states, counties, etc.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value:
Use descriptors that identify tribal community or communities for whom
      the newspaper is published, e.g. Cheyenne newspapers, Lummi newspapers. Assign also the
      descriptor Native American newspapers.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers published during a national or state election
      year which are party affiliated and usually limited to a calendar year.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value:
Use specific descriptors, e.g. Jewish newspapers, Gay newspapers,
      etc.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers by, for, and about U.S. citizens of Latin
      American descent.

Use for newspapers advocating the strict interpretation of the
      Constitution, by which all rights not specifically delegated to the federal government belong
      to the states.

Use for newspapers published in towns which are now
      abandoned.

Use for newspapers covering news about the fine
      arts.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value:
Use specific descriptors, e.g. Baptist newspapers, Catholic newspapers,
      Non-denominational newspapers, etc.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers produced by a group or movement organized for
      spreading a particular doctrine or system of principles.

Use for local newspapers published for seasonal tourist
      audiences.

Use for newspapers about profit-making enterprises that produce or
      supply goods, services, or sources of income.

Use for newspapers published by children or specifically for
      children.

Use for newspapers of annual state agricultural
      exhibitions.

Use for local newspapers published for a particular neighborhood
      within a city or county jurisdiction.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.@value: Terms used to designate genres of newspapers.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers advocating social and political rights of women
      equal to men.

Use for newspapers written by indigenous groups living in
      Alaska.

Use for newspapers which satirize current events and
      people.
Use for newspapers associated with labor strikes.

Use for newspapers sanctioned by the U.S. or state government as
      official publishers.

Use for newspapers published or produced by political or social
      radicals or nonconformists.

Use for newspapers of limited duration established and printed in
      support of local or state political issues.

Use for newspapers published for and about the
      disabled.
Use for newspapers produced in long hand script.

Use for newspapers created by schools, but generally not by the
      student body, e.g. Indian school newspapers

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value:
Also apply other genre or subject headings for particular tribes and
      geographic locations if appropriate, e.g. Blackfoot newspapers, Lummi newspapers, Yakama
      newspapers, etc. See also note at Tribal newspapers.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers associated with the expression of visionary or
      ideal schemes for the perfection of social or political conditions.

Use for local newspapers which are primarily advertising media but
      which may include substantive local news items and articles.

Use for newspapers which feature general news and which focus on
      specific topics such as insurance, investments, marketing, etc.

Use for newspapers characterized by sensationalism, usually of a
      small size and presenting news in a concise form.

Use for newspapers published usually on a daily basis during
      annual meetings of major organizations.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value:
Use specific party descriptors, e.g. Democratic Party newspapers,
      Republican party newspapers, Whig Party newspapers, etc.

Japanese American evacuation and relocation camp
      newspapers

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers advocating abstinence from the use of alcohol
      or prohibition by law of the sale of or manufacture of alcohol.

Use for newspapers whose intended audience is
      women.

Use for newspapers published by government organizations, but not
      by official publishers, e.g. Native American newspapers published by the Bureau of Indian
      Affairs.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value:
Code bibliographic record for language. Apply other genre or subject
      headings for particular groups if appropriate.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers written by college students about their
      schools; may include local, national and world news.
Use for newspapers about multicultural issues, racial equality, or diversity. Also use for newspapers covering issues of more than one ethnic group.

Use for newspapers written, published and printed by those engaged
      in these pursuits as a pastime rather than as a profession.
Use for newspapers advocating tax reform.

Use for newspapers which regularly feature articles which speak
      out against Catholicism.
Use for newspapers produced for and by lawyers.

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#note.@value:
Use specific two-term descriptors that identify the ethnicity of the
      readership (e.g. African American newspapers, Japanese American newspapers, Chinese Canadian
      newspapers, etc.). One term applies to the readership of the newspaper who identify with a
      particular ethnicity (e.g. a publication produced by a Punjabi community would receive the
      term 'Punjabi' rather than 'Pakistani' or 'East Indian'). Another term applies to the larger
      culture in which the group resides (e.g. American, Canadian).

http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scop.@value:
Use for newspapers produced under the aegis of the Masons, Odd
      Fellows, etc.

Use for newspapers primarily intended to promote local economic
      activity by touting the assets of the community.
